	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>Potential expansion of Kenyan long-life milk production could raise regional concerns</h1>

			
			<h4>
												05 July 2011
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p>A study by processing and packaging company Tetra Pak East Africa, reported in the regional press, has suggested that revenues from Kenyan milk production could be more than quadrupled, if more milk were processed. Tetra Pak estimates that currently ‘only 200 million litres of milk is processed’ out of a total of ‘3.7 billion litres of milk’ produced. The vast majority of Kenyan milk production is consumed at the point of production, sold raw or simply goes to waste. To fully realise the commercial potential of milk production, Tetra Pak argues that ‘the country will have to re-think its dairy sector development strategy, invest in the necessary infrastructure as well as give the necessary incentives to encourage the private sector to build more milk processing plants’.</p><p>Tetra Pak sees increased production of long-life milk as an important means of ironing out cyclical surpluses and shortages, and of benefit to both consumers and milk producers.</p><p>The company’s newly launched long-life milk campaign not only aims to boost consumption of long-life milk, but also to support dairy farmers through the creation of ‘dairy hubs’ to facilitate milk collection and facilitate ‘the installation of ultra-heating equipment at leading processing plants’.</p><p>Across the border in Tanzania, however, experts are warning of the imminent collapse of the dairy sector, reporting ‘stiff competition from well established players in the East African Community common market’. According to an expert quoted in the report, ‘most of the local milk processors lack technologies and adequate facilities to produce quality dairy products for export and local consumption.’ Mr Gregor Schafer from Dairy Consulting told the Tanzanian press that ‘the government has to devise policies that protect local dairy industries against cheap imports from other countries as the unfair competition curtails the growth of budding local milk factories’. While there are currently 30 milk processors in Tanzania, ‘only seven of them are considered to be major players’. According to the Chairman of Eastern and Southern African Dairy Federation, Alnoor Hussein, there is a need to develop a model for regional dairy production which ‘meets international benchmark[s] without denying the African primary producer of their livelihoods by driving them out of business’, including by the application of stringent hygiene and quality standards.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p>
<i>TheCattleSite.com</i>, ‘Kenya dairy sector to quadruple in size’, 31 May 2011<br />

<a href="http://www.thedairysite.com/news/34687/kenya-dairy-sector-to-quadruple-in-size" target="_self">http://www.thedairysite.com/news/34687/kenya-dairy-sector-to-quadruple-i...</a><br />
<i>The Citizen </i>(Dar es Salaam), ‘State of nation’s dairy sector alarms top expert’, 28 May 2011 <br />

<a href="http://allafrica.com/stories/201105301709.html" target="_self">http://allafrica.com/stories/201105301709.html</a><br />
<i>Nairobi Star </i>(Nairobi), ‘Tetra Pak kicks off long life milk campaign’, 31 May 2011<br />
<a href="http://allafrica.com/stories/201106010039.html" target="_self">http://allafrica.com/stories/201106010039.html</a></p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p>Any push for expanded production of long-life milk in Kenya by increasing the shelf life of liquid milk would be likely to intensify competition from Kenyan dairy processors on regional markets within the East African Community Customs Union. Attempts by national governments to provide financial assistance or incentives to investment in long-life milk production of the type called for by Tetra Pak is likely to raise issues of unfair competition within the single customs union market.</p><p>This highlights the importance of moving towards the establishment of commonly agreed rules on the extension of government support for investment in value-added processing in key agro-food sectors. If such commonly agreed rules are not established and respected, national producers affected by the resulting intensification of competition are likely to call for the reintroduction of restrictions on trade in dairy products. Any government action in response to such calls would undermine the free flow of goods within the EAC customs union.</p>
		</div>
		
